# Origin & Character
# Fandango: One of the oldest Spanish dance forms
# Pre-flamenco roots, likely 17th century or earlier
# Character: Lively, proud, courtship dance
# Many regional variants: Fandangos de Huelva, Fandangos Grandes, etc.
# Became a parent form for Malaguena, Granainas, Tarantas

# Compas Reference
# Time signature: 3/4 (triple meter)
# Feel: Waltz-like pulse, strong beat 1
# Often alternates free (cante) sections with compas (guitar) sections
# Fandangos Grandes: free rhythm; Fandangos de Huelva: strict compas

# Scale Reference
# E Phrygian Dominant (5th mode of A harmonic minor)
# E-F-G#-A-B-C-D
# Mixes Phrygian and Phrygian Dominant freely
# The G vs G# ambiguity is a signature color:
#   G natural (Phrygian) = darker, minor feel
#   G# (Phrygian Dominant) = brighter, Spanish flavor
# Players often alternate between both for expressive contrast

# Zone-Tritone Connection
# bII -> I (F -> E) zone-crossing resolution
# E=4(Z1), F=5(Z2) -- ZONE CROSS
# Tritone: G#-D (3rd & b7 of E7) resolves to A minor (parent)
# The Phrygian/Phrygian Dominant mixing adds zone complexity

# Harmony Reference
# Key: E Phrygian Dominant (E-F-G#-A-B-C-D)
# Typical chords: E(I) - F(bII) - G(bIII) - Am(iv)
# Cadence: Am - G - F - E (Andalusian)
# The E major chord at cadence end = Phrygian Dominant resolution
# Modal play: bIII can be G major (Phrygian) or G# dim (Dominant)

# Relationship to Other Palos
# Fandango is the parent form for:
#   Malaguena (rubato fandango from Malaga)
#   Granainas (fandango from Granada)
#   Tarantas (fandango from mining regions)
# All share Phrygian Dominant harmony with regional variations

